d208c-43 | 2026-06-09T13:16:32Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | User: but its still quite coupled to nostr? I would think the taxonomy would be abstract enough to support any other transport, for example the nip29 stuff should be completely about the nip29 codec \n  \n Assistant: You're right to push on this. Let me check where the actual type boundary sits before answering. \n  \n Assistant: You're correct, and it's worth being precise about *where* the coupling actually is — because the domain layer is clean, but the swap-seam is drawn one level too low. \n  \n ## What's actually abstract vs. what only looks abstract \n  \n **Genuinely transport-agnostic:** `domain.rs` and `SubScope`. `DomainEvent` names no kind, no tag, no relay. `SubScope` is abstract intent (`authors`, `project`, `mentions_to`, `owners`). *These two types are your real abstract taxonomy* — they could feed gRPC, MLS-native, libp2p gossipsub, anything. \n  \n **Not abstract — nostr all the way down:** the `Codec` trait itself. Look at the signatures: \n  \n ```rust \n fn encode(&self, ev: &DomainEvent) -> Result<EventBuilder>;   // nostr_sdk \n fn decode(&self, event: &Event) -> Option<DomainEvent>;        // nostr_sdk \n fn filters(&self, scope: &SubScope) -> Vec<Filter>;            // nostr_sdk \n ``` \n  \n `EventBuilder`, `Event`, `Filter` are all `nostr_sdk::prelude`. So a `Codec` impl can only ever be **another nostr wire-shape**. The seam swaps *NIPs*, not *transports*. The wiki's "intended swap-ins" — NMP (nostr), Marmot (MLS-*over*-nostr) — confirm the design quietly assumed the wire is always nostr events. "Support any transport" is true only inside the nostr family. \n  \n The most-coupled verb is `filters`. `Vec<Filter>` bakes in relay REQ semantics — a push/gossip transport doesn't subscribe by filter at all, it has a different fetch model entirely. That verb can't survive a real transport swap. \n  \n ## The NIP-29 point — you're half-right \n  \n The NIP-29 group management *is* inside the codec (`kind1.rs`), not in `domain` — so it's not leaking into the abstract layer. Good. **But** it's fused into `Kind1Codec` specifically: \n  \n - `group_create` / `group_lock_closed` / `group_put_user` are free functions hanging off the `kind1` module \n - the 39000/39001/39002 group-state subscriptions are hardcoded into `Kind1Codec::filters` (`kind1.rs:358`) \n  \n NIP-29 is an **access-control / addressing** concern, orthogonal to "how do I shape a Presence event." You could run the exact same five `DomainEvent` wire shapes over plain author-gated relays *or* over NIP-29 closed groups. Today those two axes are welded together in one struct. So your instinct is right: NIP-29 shouldn't be a property of the kind1 *event codec* — it's a property of a nostr *transport/ACL strategy*.
