ab999-58 | 2026-06-09T21:57:33Z | session:ab9998c4-6e65-410e-b298-122a2072171c |  \n Assistant: You're right, and it's worth stating plainly: **authorization must come from the signer's pubkey + its NIP-29 group membership, never from a self-asserted tag.** A pubkey is either in the group (heed it) or it isn't (don't route). An `agent` tag anyone can write carries zero authority — and if we ever did care, we'd look at who signed the event. So using its presence/absence to decide routing is backwards. \n  [...] - **Routing/admission of an inbound `p`-tagged kind:1:** look up `event.pubkey` in the group membership (the `membership` table / NIP-29 `39002`). The owner is a group admin/member and the agents are members — so a single check (*is the signer a member?*) admits both agent↔agent traffic and the owner's notes, and drops everyone else. `session-id`/`p` only decide *which* inbox, never *whether*. \n - **The slug** (display: "from claude" vs "from operator") comes from the signer's profile (kind:0 `{"name": slug}`) keyed by pubkey, or "operator" if the signer is an owner. The `agent` tag is at most a denormalized convenience to skip a profile lookup — and even that disambiguates nothing the pubkey doesn't, since sibling sessions share both pubkey *and* slug. It should never touch the routing decision.
